6. Git and GitHub
   Download for Linux Release
   https://git-scm.com/

   Create (Sign up) a account is github OR Sign in
   https://github.com/
   
   STEPS
   1. For the latest stable version for your release of Debian/Ubuntu
   $ sudo apt-get update
   $ sudo apt-get install git

   2. For Ubuntu, this PPA provides the latest stable upstream Git version
      Adding this PPA to your system
      (You can update your system with unsupported packages from this untrusted PPA by adding ppa:git-core/ppa to your system's       
      Software Sources.)
 
      $ sudo add-apt-repository ppa:git-core/ppa
      $ sudo apt-get update
     
      Set a user name for git   
      $ git config --global user.name "ericchong1122"
      $ git config --global user.email "qyms88@gmail.com"

   3. Create Directory 
      $ sudo mkdir /hoe/eric/gitrepo

      ALLOW PERMISSION FOR gitrepo Directory
      $ sudo su
  
      OUTPUT: (after sudo su)
      eric@eric-ubuntu:~/gitrepo$ sudo su
      root@eric-ubuntu:/home/eric/gitrepo# ls
      root@eric-ubuntu:/home/eric/gitrepo# pwd
      /home/eric/gitrepo
      root@eric-ubuntu:/home/eric/gitrepo# 
   

      Quick setup — if you’ve done this kind of thing before
      or	HTTPS |  SSH https://github.com/ericchong1122/gitrepo.git
      We recommend every repository include a README, LICENSE, and .gitignore.

      …or create a new repository on the command line

      echo "# gitrepo" >> README.md
      git init
      git add README.md
      git commit -m "first commit"
      git remote add origin https://github.com/ericchong1122/gitrepo.git
      git push -u origin master

      …or push an existing repository from the command line
      git remote add origin https://github.com/ericchong1122/gitrepo.git
      git push -u origin master

      …or import code from another repository
      You can initialize this repository with code from a Subversion, Mercurial, or TFS project.


      ***SUMMARY 

      Install Git with Apt : 
      $ sudo apt-get update
      $ sudo apt-get install git

      Set Up Git:
      $ git config --global user.name "Your Name"
      $ git config --global user.email "youremail@domain.com"


